definitions.definition: ( transitive , obsolete , UK , dialectal ) To part , separate or divide .
examples: To shed the sheep from the lambs.
A metal comb shed her golden hair.
We are shed with each other by an enormous distance.

definitions.definition: ( ambitransitive ) To part with , separate from, leave off ; cast off , cast , let fall, be divested of.
examples: You must shed your fear of the unknown before you can proceed.
When we found the snake, it was in the process of shedding its skin.

definitions.definition: ( transitive , archaic ) To pour ; to make flow.
( transitive ) To allow to flow or fall.
examples: I didn't shed many tears when he left me.

definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To radiate , cast , give off (light).
examples: Can you shed any light on this problem?

definitions.definition: ( obsolete , transitive ) To pour forth, give off, impart .
( obsolete , intransitive ) To fall in drops; to pour.
To sprinkle ; to intersperse ; to cover .
( weaving ) To divide, as the warp threads , so as to form a shed, or passageway, for the shuttle .
